  "prompt": "When do the rabies symptoms occur in humans?",
  "response": "Rabies symptoms typically appear 2-3 months after infection, but the incubation period can range from 1 week to several years. The timeline can vary depending on factors like:\n\n1. Bite location\n- Bites closer to the brain (head, neck) tend to develop symptoms faster\n- Bites farther from the brain (legs, feet) may have longer incubation periods\n\n2. Typical symptom progression:\n- Initial symptoms: Fever, headache, general weakness\n- Later stages: Anxiety, confusion, agitation\n- Final stages: Hallucinations, hydrophobia (fear of water), paralysis, coma\n\n3. Critical note: Once clinical symptoms appear, rabies is almost always fatal.\n\n4. Recommended actions:\n- Seek immediate medical attention after any animal bite\n- Get post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) vaccination\n- Clean wound thoroughly\n\nThe wide variation in incubation period makes early prevention and treatment crucial in preventing the disease from becoming fatal.",
